 the twentieth century, individuals including future Minister of Culture and Education Zdenek Nejedlý attacked the UB for not being nationalistic enough, producing their own revisionist histories of Smetana and his works. Kelly St. Pierre investigates Smetana as both nationalist composer and national symbol, revealing the composer'slegacy as a dynamic figure whose mythology has been rewritten time and time again to suit changing political perspectives. Kelly St. Pierre is assistant professor of musicology at Wichita State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aComposersvBiographyzCzech Republic. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / Individual Composer & Musician.2bisacsh  aBohemia.  aCommunism.  aCzech Republic.  aCzech music.  aCzechoslovakia.  aFolk music Music criticism.  aLibuse.  aLiszt.  aMoldau.  aWagner.  aZdenek Nejedly.  amusic drama.  anationalism.  anationalistic music.  aopera.  asymphonic poem.  asymphony.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782049364423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782049364/original  a978-3-11-143130-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles